   339	- 2026-04-26 [discipline][stack] **Discipline propagates only when ALL of {rules, skills, hooks, scripts} are user-level reachable from the workspace where the agent is launched.** Sprint 7c put rules + hooks user-level but missed skills; Sprint 7f closed that. Failure mode: if any one layer is workspace-scoped, agents in sibling workspaces silently fall back to first-principles exploration. Pattern checklist for future global discipline: (1) rule symlink at `~/.cursor/rules/<rule>.mdc`, (2) skill symlink at `~/.cursor/skills-cursor/<skill>/`, (3) hook entry in `~/.cursor/hooks.json` (or symlink) with shim at `~/.cursor/hooks/<shim>.sh`, (4) wrapper script under `~/.cursor-daybook-sync/scripts/` referenced by both. Skipping any one layer silently breaks the chain.
   340	- 2026-04-26 [auto-review][sticky-alert] **Acknowledging an auto-review alert in chat is not the fix; the alert must keep injecting until the metric heals.** Sprint 7d auto-review surfaced PROSE density 18.54% > 12% threshold; agent (me) replied "re-pinning caveman" and kept writing prose. Behavioural fix proven unreliable in same reply that names the problem. Structural fix in `prompt_resume_guard.sh` (Sprint 7g): hard-severity recs (PROSE / BLOAT / ORCHESTRATION / BOOT / DAYBOOK prefixes in `review-latest.json`) inject as `user_message` on EVERY prompt until next `stop` hook's auto-review clears them. Resume-class prompts get alerts + full boot dump; non-resume prompts get alerts-only short note. No alerts → clean passthrough, zero noise. Pattern: every monitoring signal needs a "stays-on-until-cleared" injection path, not just a one-shot reminder.
   341	- 2026-04-26 [reconcile][unique-vs-main] **`git rev-list --left-right --count origin/main...<branch>` + `git log <branch> --not origin/main --oneline` is the cheapest 2-line reconcile that proves a branch is/isn't fully merged.** When `git log <branch> --not origin/main` returns zero unique commits, the branch is fully contained in main even if `git branch --merged` doesn't list it (because of merge-strategy artefacts). Used this in Sprint 7h to confirm three "abandon-able" wp/worker branches (`wp-b-rotation-slice`, `wp-f-post-import-tuning`, `worker/wp-e-pamuser-smoke`) all have 0 unique commits — fully merged via PR #2 / `bc34fa4` / `4e5d439`. Pattern beats `--merged` for cross-branch-rename and squash-merge cases.
   342	- 2026-04-26 [reconcile][duplicate-rebase] **A `cursor/<topic>` branch and a `cursor/<topic>-resume-<n>` twin almost always means Cursor auto-resumed after a context boundary and produced a parallel rebase.** Discovered for `cursor/rotation-drift-suppress` vs `cursor/rotation-drift-resume-8590`: same commit message, identical functional diff vs main, but the resume branch was rebased AFTER the orchestration prune (PR #11), so it carries 124 clean lines while the original carries 1295 lines (+1171 of orchestration drift). Always pick the rebased twin; it will pass scope-fence CI. Pattern: when two branches share a commit message + diff, compare line counts of `git diff --stat origin/main...<branch>` — the smaller diff is the canonical one.
   343	- 2026-04-26 [pr-drafts][gh-absent] **PR drafts land as a workspace markdown file when `gh` CLI is missing — never inside the delivery repo.** Sprint 7h wrote `Cursor tests/PR_DRAFTS_2026-04-26.md` with title + body + `/pull/new/<branch>` URL per branch. Putting them inside `declarative-sdk-for-k/` would be caught by the scope-fence CI on the first PR cycle (matches `docs/SDK_*` or naked-root markdown patterns historically). The workspace parent is the right home for any orchestration artefact that ought to be temporary; clean up after the PRs land.
