   356	- 2026-04-26 [token-rotation][refresh-vs-login-race] **`gh auth refresh` device-flow is unreliable for rotating an active OAuth token; use `gh auth logout` + plain `gh auth login --web` instead.** Sprint 7h-5: round-1 `gh auth refresh -h github.com -s repo,workflow,gist,read:org` ran the device-code dance to a clean `✓ Authentication complete` finish, but the resulting `gho_pi5E...` token returned `401 Bad credentials` on every API call. `gh auth status` confirmed `Failed to log in... token in keyring is invalid`. Round-2 `gh auth logout -h github.com` then plain `gh auth login --hostname github.com --git-protocol https --web` (same UX, different code path) produced a working token (`gho_Qiex...`) on first try. Hypothesis: `auth refresh` re-uses an existing OAuth grant slot at github.com's end; if the device-code redemption races with the prior grant's invalidation, the new token can be persisted-locally-but-not-activated-server-side. `auth login` with explicit logout-first sidesteps this by treating the flow as a fresh authorization, not a refresh. Pattern: for any OAuth token rotation that requires a working credential at the end, `logout → login` is the safe path; `refresh` is a fragile shortcut that can leave you with an invalid-but-stored token. Caveat: `gh auth login` defaults to scopes `gist read:org repo` (no `workflow`); pass `-s workflow` explicitly if pushes need to touch `.github/workflows/`. Server-side revocation of the OLD token is not programmatically achievable with user-token auth — `DELETE /applications/{client_id}/token` requires the OAuth app's client_secret which is not public for `gh`. Bound the leak to local agent-transcript files and accept residual risk; nuclear option is revoking the whole "GitHub CLI" OAuth app authorization at github.com/settings/applications, which kills new token too.
   357	- 2026-04-26 [branch-stack][pollution] **A branch created with HEAD on a non-main branch will silently inherit that ancestor's commits, polluting the PR diff and breaking CI on repo-wide checks (ruff format, mypy) even when the slice diff is clean.** Sprint 7h-5: 3 cov branches (`cov-redact-patterns`, `cov-schema-validation`, `cov-normalize-edges`) were created while parent was on `cursor/sdk-ksm-bootstrap`, dragging in 3 KSM commits and 3 unformatted KSM files (`auth/helper.py`, `secrets/ksm.py`, `_fakes/commander.py`). PRs targeted `main`, but `ruff format --check .` runs repo-wide, so the inherited unformatted files tripped the lint check despite the slice diff being immaculate. Diagnostic: `git log --oneline origin/main..origin/cursor/<branch>` shows the polluted ancestry — should be exactly 1 commit for a single-slice branch. Fix: `git rebase --onto origin/main <pollution-tip-sha> cursor/<branch>` drops the polluting commits and leaves only the slice on top of main. Pattern: every worker-spawn helper (`codex_offline.sh`, `git worktree add`) should explicitly `git checkout main && git pull` BEFORE creating the new branch, or pass `git worktree add -b <new> <path> origin/main` to pin the base. Scope-fence + branch-hygiene contracts already say "branch from main" in prose; needs to be enforced structurally in the helper scripts. Verifiable post-rebase: file count delta vs main matches the slice's expected file count (e.g. `git diff --name-only main...HEAD` lists only the slice's files). Future: add a slice-precommit check that fails if `git merge-base <branch> origin/main != origin/main`'s recent HEAD (i.e. the branch is N commits ahead of a stale main rather than the current main).
