   363	- 2026-04-26 [worktree-triage][cherry-pick-probe] **Use `git cherry-pick --no-commit -X theirs <sha>` against current main as the canonical "is this old branch's content already subsumed" probe; if `git diff --cached --stat` shows mostly DELETIONS (very few inserts), the branch is dead.** Sprint 7h-8 codex/* triage: 3 long-lived `codex/*` worktrees (rotation-apply, tuning-apply, gateway-projects-design) accumulated divergent commits while their content was being canonicalised through PR #2's "v1.1 capability slices" rebase + merge to main. Surface-level `git log <branch> --not main --oneline` showed each branch had a "unique" commit; surface-level `git diff main..branch --stat` showed hundreds of differing lines. But cherry-pick dry-run revealed each branch was ≥99% subsumed: rotation = 6 ins / 305 del, tuning = 31 ins / 307 del, gateway = 1 ins / 2 del. Pattern: when the parent has rebased and re-landed work via a different branch, the original branch's diff vs main looks large in BOTH directions because of formatting/refactor drift; the cherry-pick probe is the only way to distinguish "actually contains net-new work" from "stale snapshot of work that's already on main". Decision rule: < 10 net inserts after cherry-pick → tear down with recovery SHA. > 50 net inserts → revive into a fresh worktree + rebase. 10–50 → manual review. Always preserve recovery SHAs in the daybook before deleting branches; orphan commits stay reachable in the reflog for ~30 days but aren't grep-able from the journal afterwards.
